grown up about Horace, it is meant to be distinctly a study of the poet himself, andis intended especially for the college class- room. IN the Brutos, which was composed in 46 nc. and purports to

be a conversation with Atticus and Brutus, Cicero traces the development of oratory among the Romans down to his own time, with critical notices oi about two hundred speakers. The long catalogue is relieved oi dryness by the dialogus form, the freedom of digression, and by Cicero’s fresh and teeming style.

Professor Kellogg has edited the work especially for college read- ing. The introductiou touches upon points of interest to those to whom Cicero is no stranger, and contains a full conspectus. The notes deal with the subject-matter, historical relations, and diction of the dialogue rather than with the commonplaces of grammar. Parallel passages are freely given, especially from Cicero’s other rhetorical works and from Quintilian.
